+{"type":"message","id":"7d1ec67a","parentId":"c603e0dc","timestamp":"2026-03-28T18:56:50.980Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Operator notes for this run:\n## Operator note — 2026-03-28T18:27:01.073Z\n\nRefer to health-check/health-check.txt and address\n\nThese notes are authoritative user steering for this run. Follow them unless they directly conflict with the repository state or the controller's explicit task.\n\nParent conversation handoff summary:\nParent conversation handoff summary\nSummary model: anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5\nSource items: 265\n\nOverview:\nST6 is an enterprise software company enabling weekly commit-based planning with AI assistance. The session discussed how to make AI integral to the product (not bolted-on) and reviewed an evaluation pipeline for AI quality. We concluded the next milestone is implementing enforceable AI quality thresholds via: adding a critical field to eval cases, wiring two existing LLM judge prompts (title-quality, criteria-quality) into the PromptEvalRunner, committing the most recent eval run as a regression baseline, creating an eval-thresholds.json config, building a Node.js enforcement script that compares results against thresholds and baseline, and integrating that into CI.\n\nSettled decisions:\n- Judge thresholds must be 3-layer: deterministic gates first (schema+case pass rate), LLM judge absolute thresholds second, regression relative thresholds third.\n- Split judge thresholds by risk: high-stakes features (risk signals, insights, RAG) get stricter thresholds (faithfulness >= 0.90) than assistive features (draft, lint, suggestions) which get more permissive thresholds (faithfulness >= 0.85).\n- Deterministic thresholds are hard-gates that block CI; judge and regression thresholds initially soft-gate (report but don't block) until stable.\n- Use eval-baseline.json as regression anchor committed to the repo. When eval runs, the enforcement script compares the latest results to both the config thresholds and the baseline snapshot.\n- Judge scoring in the eval pipeline is optional: if OPENROUTER_API_KEY is not set, judge dimensions are skipped, not failed.\n- The enforcement script will be a standalone Node.js script (scripts/eval-threshold-check.js) using only Node 20 built-ins, runnable outside Gradle.\n- After step 2, the title-quality and criteria-quality judge prompts will be wired into PromptEvalRunner for draft-assist cases to produce real judge scores for calibration.\n\nConstraints / must-remember items:\n- All work is backend-test-only for steps 1-2; do not modify any main or frontend source files during those steps.\n- Java code must pass spotlessCheck (Eclipse JDT formatter).\n- PromptEvalRunner parameterized test structure must be preserved, not replaced.\n- FaithfulnessEvaluator.java (runtime judge, separate from eval pipeline) must not be modified.\n- Eval runner is @Tag(\"eval\") and excluded from normal test runs — preserve that behavior.\n- Judge scoring must be optional: skip if provider unavailable (no API key), don't fail.\n- Eval results write to backend/build/eval-results/ — keep that path.\n- Step 3 requires exactly 6 test cases marked as critical: 3 in draft-assist (draft-001, draft-004, draft-008) and 3 in commit-lint (lint-001, lint-003, lint-004).\n- Regression thresholds must be configurable via eval-thresholds.json, not hardcoded in script logic.\n\nOpen questions:\n- Should the enforcement script exit 0 or 1 when judge scores are unavailable (API key missing)? Currently plan says skip those checks and pass on deterministic, but CI teams may want a clear signal.\n- The eval-baseline.json in step 3 references an old run timestamp (2026-03-26). Should we run a fresh eval before committing baseline to ensure the cases are stable?\n- How should the enforcement script integrate with existing Gradle eval tasks — should it be invoked inside build.gradle or externally in CI?\n- Do we want the threshold config to be versioned per prompt-version (e.g., separate thresholds for commit-draft-assist-v1 vs v2), or single global thresholds for all versions of a suggestion type?\n\nUse this handoff as background context. If it conflicts with the explicit task below or the current repository state, prioritize the explicit task and repo state.\n\nPlan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Implement enforceable AI quality thresholds by: (1) adding a `critical` field to eval cases, (2) wiring the existing title-quality and criteria-quality LLM judge prompts into `PromptEvalRunner` so draft-assist cases collect real judge scores, (3) committing the most recent eval output as a regression baseline and creating an `eval-thresholds.json` config, (4) building a threshold enforcement script that reads eval results and compares against the config + baseline, (5) wiring that script into the GitLab `eval:llm-judge` job, and (6) adding unit tests for the enforcement script. The result is a pipeline where deterministic checks hard-gate, judge scores soft-gate with clear pass/fail reporting, and regressions against baseline are detected. Constraints: backend-only for steps 1-3 (no frontend modifications); Java must pass spotlessCheck; preserve existing PromptEvalRunner parameterized test structure; judge scoring is optional (skip if no OPENROUTER_API_KEY); do NOT modify FaithfulnessEvaluator.java; eval results write to backend/build/eval-results/; enforcement script is standalone Node.js (scripts/eval-threshold-check.js) using only Node 20 built-ins.\",\n  \"totalSteps\": 6,\n  \"stepTitles\": [\n    \"1. Add `critical` field to EvalCase/EvalResult and mark critical cases in fixture JSON\",\n    \"2. Wire title-quality and criteria-quality LLM judges into PromptEvalRunner for draft-assist cases\",\n    \"3. Commit the most recent eval run as baseline and create eval-thresholds.json\",\n    \"4. Build the threshold enforcement script\",\n    \"5. Split CI into two jobs: eval run (manual/allow_failure) + threshold check (hard-gate), and add npm scripts\",\n    \"6. Add unit tests for the enforcement script and verify end-to-end\"\n  ]\n}\n\nStep 6: Add unit tests for the enforcement script and verify end-to-end\n{\n  \"id\": \"step-6\",\n  \"title\": \"Add unit tests for the enforcement script and verify end-to-end\",\n  \"description\": \"Create `scripts/__tests__/eval-threshold-check.test.js` that tests the threshold check logic with synthetic eval results. The test must `require()` the exported functions from `scripts/eval-threshold-check.js` (see Step 4 architecture). Use Node 20's built-in test runner (`node:test` module) and `node:assert`. Use CommonJS since root package.json does not have `\\\"type\\\": \\\"module\\\"`.\\n\\nTest cases:\\n- All passing → no violations\\n- Schema validity failure → violation reported\\n- Critical case failure → violation reported\\n- Regression detected (pass rate drop) → violation reported\\n- Missing judge scores → skip judge checks, pass on deterministic only\\n- Missing baseline → skip regression checks, warn\\n\\nThe test should be runnable via `node --test scripts/__tests__/eval-threshold-check.test.js`.\\n\\nUpdate `package.json` root `test` script to also run the script tests so the `unit` check picks them up. The current `test` script is: `npm run test -w frontend -- --run && npm run test -w @weekly-commit/shared -- --run && cd backend && ./gradlew test`. **CRITICAL working directory bug to avoid**: the `cd backend && ./gradlew test` portion leaves the shell cwd inside `backend/`. You MUST `cd` back to the repo root before running the node tests. Append `&& cd .. && node --test scripts/__tests__/*.test.js` (NOT just `&& node --test ...` which would resolve the glob to `backend/scripts/__tests__/` which does not exist).\\n\\nScope: Create files in `scripts/__tests__/` and update `package.json`.\",\n  \"requiredChecks\": [\n    \"unit\",\n    \"build\"\n  ]\n}\n\nThis is relay round 2. Another agent has already worked on this step.\n\nYou are in VERIFICATION MODE. Your default action is to APPROVE.\nFocus your review on the DIFF — the changes made in the previous round.\nOnly make changes if there is a MATERIAL defect: failing check, missing step requirement, logic bug, or security issue.\nStyle preferences, alternative approaches, comment wording, and optional polish are NOT grounds for changes.\n\nIf all checks pass and the step requirements are met, approve immediately.\nLog anything else you notice as observations — do not act on them.\n\nPrevious agent's notes:\n## Summary\n\n**What I implemented for Step 6:**\n\n**`scripts/__tests__/eval-threshold-check.test.js`** — 22 tests across 8 `describe` blocks using `node:test` + `node:assert/strict` (CommonJS, no external deps):\n\n| Suite | Tests |\n|---|---|\n| `computeMetrics` | 7 — empty results, all-passing, partial failure, critical rates, judge score grouping, resultCountsByType |\n| `checkThresholds — all passing` | 2 — no hard failures, correct check object shape |\n| `checkThresholds — schema validity failure` | 1 — hard violation reported |\n| `checkThresholds — critical case failure` | 2 — hard violation when critical fails, skip when none present |\n| `checkThresholds — missing judge scores` | 3 — no hard fail, soft informational note emitted, judge check fires when scores present |\n| `checkRegression — missing baseline` | 2 — null baseline skipped, empty baseline skipped |\n| `checkRegression — pass rate drop` | 2 — large drop flagged as soft failure, no drop passes |\n| `checkRegression — critical failures added` | 3 — new critical regression detected, new case not in baseline is ok, pre-existing failure is ok |\n\n**`package.json`** — Updated `test` script:\n```\n... && cd backend && ./gradlew test && cd .. && node --test scripts/__tests__/*.test.js\n```\nThe `cd ..` correctly navigates back from `backend/` to the repo root before the glob resolves.\n\n**All checks:**\n- `node --test scripts/__tests__/eval-threshold-check.test.js` → 22 pass, 0 fail ✅\n- `./gradlew build -x test` → `BUILD SUCCESSFUL` ✅\n\nVerdict: changes_made\n\nPrior observations from earlier steps (address if they fall within this step's scope):\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/evidence/LineageQueryService.java, StructuredEvidenceService.java: Untracked files in working directory (from a previous session), not committed to git. These caused pre-existing spotless violations that I fixed via spotlessApply.\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ai/controller/AiController.java, backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/UserWeekFactRepository.java: These are modified in the working tree relative to HEAD but aren't part of any current step. They should be committed in the appropriate step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 2: callJudge() creates a new HttpClient instance per invocation. For the eval runner this is fine (low call volume), but if call frequency increased it would be better to reuse a single instance. Out of scope for this step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 2 package.json / future step 6: The health-check flags a likely cwd bug in the planned npm test chaining (`cd backend && ./gradlew test && node --test ...`). That is outside this step’s scope, but should be fixed when step 6 is implemented.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 step-6 / package.json: The health-check’s cwd warning about `cd backend && ./gradlew test && node --test ...` still looks valid and should be handled when step 6 is implemented.\n- [MEDIUM] step 4: The script's `findLatestEvalResult()` picks the lexicographically last filename. Since filenames use the pattern `eval-<ISO-timestamp>.json` with colons replaced by dashes, this sorts correctly — but if any non-timestamp `.json` files were dropped in that directory, they could be picked erroneously. Out of scope.\n- [MEDIUM] step 4 package.json / future step 6: The health-check warning about `cd backend && ./gradlew test && node --test ...` still appears valid and should be fixed when step 6 is implemented.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 package.json / future step 6: The health-check warning about appending `node --test ...` after `cd backend && ./gradlew test` still appears valid and should be handled when step 6 is implemented.\n\nFiles changed so far:\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-28T18-01-07-371Z-cc2c5bdb/cost.json\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-28T18-01-07-371Z-cc2c5bdb/sessions/continuous/relay-a/2026-03-28T18-31-36-549Z_a7489b6f-23f6-4427-b326-8842497fc61f.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-28T18-01-07-371Z-cc2c5bdb/state.json\npackage.json\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-28T18-01-07-371Z-cc2c5bdb/steps/6\nscripts/__tests__\n\nWhen done, explain what you reviewed, what you changed (if anything), and your assessment.\n\nEnd with:\nVerdict: approve  — if the step is complete and correct, no more changes needed\nVerdict: changes_made  — if you made fixes or improvements\nVerdict: replan_needed  — if the step is structurally impossible to complete as planned and needs controller-managed replanning"}],"timestamp":1774724210979}}
